{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:53:49.321Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Verifying Success Metrics**\n\nI'm pleased to report that the verification script has passed all 25 tests, confirming the accuracy of Blueprint scoring, ROI calculations, recommendations, and helpers. I'm now turning my attention to `components/portal/SecureLogin.tsx` to examine it in more detail.\n\n\n**Improving Secure Login**\n\nI'm now diving into the `SecureLogin.tsx` file, specifically the OTP input. My focus is on crafting a superior 6-digit input component that's more user-friendly. I'm aiming for a custom design that supports key presses, pasting, and auto-focusing across the individual input fields, while also gracefully handling initial autofill with a default code like `102486` when the sandbox role changes. I am currently working on the JSX rendering structure.\n\n\n**Adding OTP Timer**\n\nI've got the six-digit input fields structured, now I'm shifting to enhancing the user experience. I'm focused on integrating an animated circular timer beside the \"Multi-Factor OTP Code\" label, counting down from 30 seconds. Upon reset, the system will rotate the simulated code and log a telemetry message. The countdown should automatically start when `authMethod` equals \"otp.\"\n\n\n**Refining Timer Logic**\n\nI'm now carefully crafting the countdown timer's logic within the `useEffect` hook. I'm focusing on ensuring it resets to 30 seconds when the \"otp\" authentication method is active. The system will rotate the simulated code upon timer expiry and log a telemetry message. I'm taking steps to handle the situation if the user is typing the code. I am exploring approaches to enable the user to still be able to interact with the component.\n\n\n**Defining OTP Key Generation**\n\nI'm now determining the behavior when the \"Generate Code\" button is clicked. It will log telemetry and set the OTP code to \"102486,\" the expected mock value. This fits well with the current active countdown and allows user input. I'm also ensuring the six input refs are correctly declared at the component's top. I am currently working on making sure the array of refs is rendered correctly.\n\n\n**Reviewing Forgot Password**\n\nI'm now switching gears to the \"forgot password\" flow. I'm focusing on the visual design of the modal, aiming for a premium feel. Currently, the modal renders when `showForgot` is true. Next, I am investigating the state when `forgotSubmitted` is true, looking at the UI elements to ensure they fit a premium design aesthetic.\n\n\n**Designing Forgot Password**\n\nI'm now focusing on the UI of the \"forgot password\" flow when `forgotSubmitted` is true. My focus is the design; specifically, rendering a notice with the `forgotEmail`, a \"Connected in backend phase\" message, and a deterministic hash for the email, all with a premium aesthetic and font choices. I will now integrate a disclaimer that it's a frontend-only design.\n\n\n"}}
